148: Sort List
Problem Statement

Given the head of a linked list, sort the list in ascending order and return the sorted list.

Examples
Input:  4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 3
Output: 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4
Input:  -1 -> 5 -> 3 -> 4 -> 0
Output: -1 -> 0 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
Intuition

Sorting a linked list efficiently requires O(n log n) time complexity. The best approach is Merge Sort, which works naturally with linked lists because:

Finding the middle is easy using Slow & Fast Pointers.
Splitting the list is straightforward.
Merging two sorted linked lists can be done efficiently.

The idea is:

Divide the linked list into two halves
        ↓
Recursively sort both halves
        ↓
Merge the sorted halves
Approach
Step 1: Find the Middle of the Linked List

Use Slow and Fast Pointers.

ListNode slow = head;
ListNode fast = head.next;

Move:

while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;
}

At the end:

slow points to the middle node.
The list can be split into two halves.
Step 2: Split the List
ListNode rightHead = slow.next;
slow.next = null;

Example:

Before:
4 -> 2 -> 1 -> 3

After:
Left  = 4 -> 2
Right = 1 -> 3
Step 3: Recursively Sort Both Halves
ListNode left = sortList(head);
ListNode right = sortList(rightHead);

Each half is recursively divided until only one node remains.

Step 4: Merge Two Sorted Lists

Merge the two sorted halves using the Merge Two Sorted Lists technique.

if (l1.val <= l2.val) {
    curr.next = l1;
    l1 = l1.next;
} else {
    curr.next = l2;
    l2 = l2.next;
}

Continue until all nodes are merged.

Code
class Solution {

    public ListNode sortList(ListNode head) {

        if (head == null || head.next == null) {
            return head;
        }

        ListNode slow = head;
        ListNode fast = head.next;

        while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
            slow = slow.next;
            fast = fast.next.next;
        }

        ListNode rightHead = slow.next;
        slow.next = null;

        ListNode left = sortList(head);
        ListNode right = sortList(rightHead);

        return merge(left, right);
    }

    private ListNode merge(ListNode l1, ListNode l2) {

        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(-1);
        ListNode curr = dummy;

        while (l1 != null && l2 != null) {

            if (l1.val <= l2.val) {
                curr.next = l1;
                l1 = l1.next;
            } else {
                curr.next = l2;
                l2 = l2.next;
            }

            curr = curr.next;
        }

        if (l1 != null) curr.next = l1;
        if (l2 != null) curr.next = l2;

        return dummy.next;
    }
}
